snippet.textDisplay:
Here is some extra information I found interesting in the original text.

1. Feels like they'll be on this journey forever.
Actually they are almost at the half way point. The book had 100 chapter, and this ep. Take place between 43~47.

2. 2:52 Monkey and the west dragon king had a nice conversation like:
Monkey: “Your sister had a mess of a family.”
Dragon: “No no no, all 8 of his brothers are good, they all get a job in the government, he is the only loser in the family.”
Like, this is soooo Chinese family talks.

3. 7:13 When Pigsy throw those statues into toilet, he offers some apologize to those statues. Which basically can be sum up as:” You had been sitting there eating good offerings for a long time now, so it’s not unfair if you eat some shit today.”

4. 9:20 Remember in last episode you need proper paper works to start the rain? Well, the reason the immortal can call in the rain is because they do get proper paper works.
Bureaucracy, right?

5. 10:44 Monkey actually did some foreshadowing here saying “You can chop off my head, cut open my belly, remove my heart, those thing are EASY. But sitting still? You can try chain me on an iron pillar and I will be twisting the entire time.”

6. 12:50 The detail that had been cut out is: Monkey wasn’t joking about cleaning his organs. He literally took his organs out, hand clean all of them, then put them back in place.

7. 13:13 What Pigsy actually said to Sandy is: “Man, we had been shit talking to each other this entire time, I’m surprised he is actually this powerful.”
You don’t say.

snippet.textDisplay: Okay I have no idea when or where else to suggest this but here goes, since I was rewatching the Greek gods videos. How about a Miscellaneous Myths on the obscure Greek god Akheilos? Aphrodite turned him into a shark for being too pretty. Not a lot of shark myths out there. Also a lot of confusion about him being son of the Lamia who is maybe or maybe not a shark? And the fact that the guy’s name seems way too much like both the river god Achelous and Achilles? And how some of the versions of the story involve the great god Pan himself as judging Akheilos the prettiest, and Pan getting cursed to chase the nymph Echo for it?!
